---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import AceArt from "../components/AceArt.astro";

const description =
  "ACE Engine: read-only analytics for GPU job right-sizing. Ingests Slurm accounting exports, scores per-job efficiency, applies a conservative safety overlay, and produces a structured report with traceable recommendations and explicit assumptions.";
---

<BaseLayout title="ACE Engine | Plain Theory Labs" description={description}>
  <section class="section prose">
    <h1>ACE Engine</h1>
    <p class="thesis">
      ACE is a read-only analytics engine for GPU job right-sizing. It ingests Slurm accounting
      exports, scores per-job efficiency against measured or estimated telemetry, applies a
      conservative safety overlay, and produces a structured report with traceable recommendations
      and explicit assumptions.
    </p>

    <p>
      Current phase: 2B0. No enforcement, no scheduler changes. ACE reads, scores, and reports.
      Policy decisions remain with the operator.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>What ACE produces</h2>

    <p>
      A per-job efficiency score. A right-sizing recommendation with a confidence label. An
      environmental impact estimate covering energy, carbon, and water, with every coefficient
      disclosed. A zero-dependency HTML report any operator can open on any machine and hand to
      any stakeholder.
    </p>

    <p>
      The MIT Supercloud run: 35,745 jobs analyzed. Average GPU utilization 25.7%. Median
      utilization 16%. Jobs under one minute 41%. Near-zero GPU activity 33%. These numbers come
      from real scheduler logs and DCGM telemetry from a published dataset.
    </p>

    <div class="visual-center" aria-hidden="true">
      <AceArt />
    </div>
    <p class="figure-caption muted">Signal to structure: noisy scheduler traces become scored, reviewable outputs.</p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Pipeline</h2>

    <p>Five deterministic stages.</p>

    <h3>Ingest</h3>
    <p>
      Slurm <code>sacct</code> export or canonical CSV enters the engine. JobID normalization
      runs. Telemetry joined where available.
    </p>

    <h3>Score</h3>
    <p>
      Per-job utilization computed. Over-request heuristic applied. Weighted review score
      assigned.
    </p>

    <h3>Safety overlay</h3>
    <p>
      Conservative guardrails block low-confidence downsizing recommendations. Nothing gets
      recommended that cannot be defended.
    </p>

    <h3>Impact estimation</h3>
    <p>
      Energy, carbon, water, and cost projections computed from physical coefficients. Every
      assumption is user-configurable and disclosed in the output.
    </p>

    <h3>Report</h3>
    <p>
      JSON payload and single-file HTML. Interactive tables, inline SVG charts, summary cards.
      No dependencies, no server, opens anywhere.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Assumptions and limits</h2>

    <p>
      Environmental impact numbers are coefficient-based estimates, not metered totals. The
      default coefficients are documented and configurable. If your site has measured PUE or
      grid carbon intensity data, use it.
    </p>

    <p>
      Phase 2B0 has no live telemetry join. GPU utilization is derived from sidecar files or
      proxy estimates where direct measurement is not available. Confidence labels reflect this.
      Phase 2B1 adds windowed telemetry joins from DCGM and Prometheus.
    </p>

    <p>
      ACE does not touch your scheduler. It does not modify job parameters, queue configurations,
      or resource limits. It reads, scores, and reports.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Status</h2>

    <p>
      Phase 2B0 complete. 118 tests passing. Validated on MIT Supercloud HPCA22 and Google Borg
      CPU proxy datasets.
    </p>

    <p>
      Phase 2B1 in progress: windowed telemetry joins, JobID normalization, per-window provenance
      scoring.
    </p>

    <p class="inline-links">
      <a href="/contact">Discuss a pilot &rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
